        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 15:8, 24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. It is used of nearly all the kings of Judah], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and was buried with his fathers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [These words go to prove, against Gesenius, that the phrase \"slept (lit. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "lay down",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") with his fathers\" is not to be interpreted of Sheol, but of the grave; see on 1 Kings 2:10] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "in the city of David. And his mother's name was Naamah, an Ammonitess.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Same words as in ver. 21. The repetition can hardly be, as Bahr, Wordsworth, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "al",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., imagine, designed, in order to show that the worship of Moloch was brought by her to Jerusalem (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and that she exercised a sinister influence upon her son. As she is twice called \"the Ammonitess\" it can hardly be doubted that she was one of the \"Ammonitesses\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Hebrews) who turned away Solomon's heart; and it is also certain that Rehoboam did not inherit his folly from his father. At the same time these words are more easily accounted for on the supposition that the historian found them in this position in one or more of the documents from which he compiled his history. It is also to be remembered that some of these chronological statements are manifestly by a later hand, and have been transferred from the margin to the text. See on 1 Kings 6:1.] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And Abijam",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [elsewhere called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Abijah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 13:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Abijahu",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 13:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Hebrews) Some MSS. have Abijah here. The variation is not easily accounted for except as a clerical error. The supposition of Lightfoot that the name was designedly altered by the historian ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " avoid the incorporation of the sacred JAH into the name of a bad man is too fanciful, the more so as Abijam was by no means an exceptionally bad king. It is, however, approved by Bahr and Rawlinson. But it is as little probable that Abijam is the original form of the name (Keil). The form ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Abijahu",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the LXX. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Ἀβιού",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the analogy of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Abiel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 9:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") all make against this idea. On the whole, it is more likely that Abijam results from an error of transcription, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "ה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and the final ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": " ם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " being easily confounded] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "his son reigned in his stead.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
